comment.text: The translation key "EnterWebhookName" is used to display a placeholder text in a web form, which is part of a modal dialog. This text prompts users to enter a webhook name when submitting the form. It appears as a label for an input field.

usage.context:
<ModalDialog.Body>
 <StyledWebhookForm onSubmit={onFormSubmit}>
 <LabledInput
 id={`${additionalId}-name-input`}
 label={t("WebhookName")}
 placeholder={t("EnterWebhookName")}
 name="name"
 value={webhookInfo.name}
 onChange={onInputChange}
 hasError={!isValid.name}
 className={isSettingsModal ? "margin-0" : ""}

ai_spell_check_issues.description: The translation "Εισαγωγή ονόματος webhook" is too literal. A more natural Greek translation would use a verb like 'εισάγετε' (enter/input) or 'καθορίστε' (specify).
The word "վեբ-կապիկ" is a literal translation of "webhook" and might be confusing to Armenian users. The established term 'վեբհուք' (webhook) is preferred.

The word 'webhook' is transliterated inconsistently. It appears as 'webhook' in the English content, but is represented as 'webhook' in the Lao translation. It's recommended to standardize the transliteration.
ai_spell_check_issues.suggestion: Consider using a consistent transliteration of 'webhook' throughout the application.

ai_spell_check_issues.description: The translation 'Ievadiet tīmekļa aizķeres nosaukumu' is not the most natural or accurate translation of 'Enter webhook name'. 'Tīmekļa aizķere' is a literal translation of 'webhook' and is not commonly used. A more natural translation would use a term more readily understood in Latvian.
The translation 'Introducere nume webhook' is a literal translation but doesn't flow naturally in Romanian. 'Introducere' implies 'introduction' rather than 'enter'.

The translation "webhook නම යොදන්න" is not the most natural or accurate translation of 'Enter webhook name'. While technically correct, it sounds somewhat clunky. A more natural phrasing would convey the instruction to 'enter' the name.

While technically correct, 'Vnesi ime webhook' is a very literal translation and sounds unnatural in Slovenian. A more idiomatic translation would be 'Vnesite ime webhooka' or 'Vnesite webhookovo ime'.
While technically correct, "Унеси webhook име" is a very literal translation and doesn't flow naturally in Serbian. It sounds somewhat awkward.

The translation 'Unesi webhook ime' is not the most natural or accurate translation of 'Enter webhook name'. It literally translates to 'Enter webhook my'. The correct translation should be something more like 'Upisite webhook ime' or 'Unesite webhook naziv'.
